#: src/index.md:45
msgid ""
"Build and publish crates with pyo3, rust-cpython, cffi and uniffi bindings "
"as well as rust binaries as python packages."
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:47
msgid ""
"This project is meant as a zero configuration replacement for [setuptools-"
"rust](https://github.com/PyO3/setuptools-rust) and [milksnake](https://"
"github.com/getsentry/milksnake). It supports building wheels for python 3.5+ "
"on windows, linux, mac and freebsd, can upload them to [pypi](https://pypi."
"org/) and has basic pypy support."
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:50
msgid "Check out the [User Guide](https://maturin.rs/)!"
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:52
msgid "Usage"
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:54
msgid ""
"You can either download binaries from the [latest release](https://github."
"com/PyO3/maturin/releases/latest) or install it with pip:"
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:60
msgid "There are four main commands:"
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:62
msgid "`maturin new` creates a new cargo project with maturin configured."
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:63
msgid ""
"`maturin publish` builds the crate into python packages and publishes them "
"to pypi."
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:64
msgid ""
"`maturin build` builds the wheels and stores them in a folder (`target/"
"wheels` by default), but doesn't upload them. It's possible to upload those "
"with [twine](https://github.com/pypa/twine) or `maturin upload`."
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:65
msgid ""
"`maturin develop` builds the crate and installs it as a python module "
"directly in the current virtualenv. Note that while `maturin develop` is "
"faster, it doesn't support all the feature that running `pip install` after "
"`maturin build` supports."
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:67
msgid ""
"`pyo3` and `rust-cpython` bindings are automatically detected. For cffi or "
"binaries, you need to pass `-b cffi` or `-b bin`. maturin doesn't need extra "
"configuration files and doesn't clash with an existing setuptools-rust or "
"milksnake configuration. You can even integrate it with testing tools such "
"as [tox](https://tox.readthedocs.io/en/latest/). There are examples for the "
"different bindings in the `test-crates` folder."
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:72
msgid ""
"The name of the package will be the name of the cargo project, i.e. the name "
"field in the `[package]` section of `Cargo.toml`. The name of the module, "
"which you are using when importing, will be the `name` value in the `[lib]` "
"section (which defaults to the name of the package). For binaries, it's "
"simply the name of the binary generated by cargo."
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:75
msgid "Python packaging basics"
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:77
msgid ""
"Python packages come in two formats: A built form called wheel and source "
"distributions (sdist), both of which are archives. A wheel can be compatible "
"with any python version, interpreter (cpython and pypy, mainly), operating "
"system and hardware architecture (for pure python wheels), can be limited to "
"a specific platform and architecture (e.g. when using ctypes or cffi) or to "
"a specific python interpreter and version on a specific architecture and "
"operating system (e.g. with pyo3 and rust-cpython)."
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:82
msgid ""
"When using `pip install` on a package, pip tries to find a matching wheel "
"and install that. If it doesn't find one, it downloads the source "
"distribution and builds a wheel for the current platform, which requires the "
"right compilers to be installed. Installing a wheel is much faster than "
"installing a source distribution as building wheels is generally slow."
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:85
msgid ""
"When you publish a package to be installable with `pip install`, you upload "
"it to [pypi](https://pypi.org/), the official package repository. For "
"testing, you can use [test pypi](https://test.pypi.org/) instead, which you "
"can use with `pip install --index-url https://test.pypi.org/simple/`. Note "
"that for publishing for linux, [you need to use the manylinux docker "
"container](#manylinux-and-auditwheel), while for publishing from your "
"repository you can use the [PyO3/maturin-action github action](https://"
"github.com/PyO3/maturin-action)."
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:89
msgid "pyo3 and rust-cpython"
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:91
msgid ""
"For pyo3 and rust-cpython, maturin can only build packages for installed "
"python versions. On linux and mac, all python versions in `PATH` are used. "
"If you don't set your own interpreters with `-i`, a heuristic is used to "
"search for python installations. On windows all versions from the python "
"launcher (which is installed by default by the python.org installer) and all "
"conda environments except base are used. You can check which versions are "
"picked up with the `list-python` subcommand."
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:95
msgid ""
"pyo3 will set the used python interpreter in the environment variable "
"`PYTHON_SYS_EXECUTABLE`, which can be used from custom build scripts. "
"Maturin can build and upload wheels for pypy with pyo3, even though only "
"pypy3.7-7.3 on linux is tested."
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:97
msgid "Cffi"
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:99
msgid ""
"Cffi wheels are compatible with all python versions including pypy. If "
"`cffi` isn't installed and python is running inside a virtualenv, maturin "
"will install it, otherwise you have to install it yourself (`pip install "
"cffi`)."
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:101
msgid ""
"maturin uses cbindgen to generate a header file, which can be customized by "
"configuring cbindgen through a `cbindgen.toml` file inside your project "
"root. Alternatively you can use a build script that writes a header file to "
"`$PROJECT_ROOT/target/header.h`."
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:103
msgid ""
"Based on the header file maturin generates a module which exports an `ffi` "
"and a `lib` object."
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:114
msgid "\"CARGO_MANIFEST_DIR\""
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:122
msgid "\"target\""
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:122
msgid "\"header.h\""
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:128
msgid "uniffi"
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:130
msgid ""
"uniffi bindings use [uniffi-rs](https://mozilla.github.io/uniffi-rs/) to "
"generate Python `ctypes` bindings from an interface definition file. uniffi "
"wheels are compatible with all python versions including pypy."
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:133
msgid "Mixed rust/python projects"
msgstr "Rust/Python 混合專案"

#: src/index.md:135
msgid ""
"To create a mixed rust/python project, create a folder with your module name "
"(i.e. `lib.name` in Cargo.toml) next to your Cargo.toml and add your python "
"sources there:"
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:149
msgid ""
"You can specify a different python source directory in `pyproject.toml` by "
"setting `tool.maturin.python-source`, for example"
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:151
msgid "**pyproject.toml**"
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:153
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"[tool.maturin]\n"
"python-source = \"python\"\n"
"module-name = \"my_project._lib_name\"\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:159
msgid "then the project structure would look like this:"
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:174
msgid "**Note**"
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:176
msgid ""
"This structure is recommended to avoid [a common `ImportError` pitfall]"
"(https://github.com/PyO3/maturin/issues/490)"
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:178
msgid ""
"maturin will add the native extension as a module in your python folder. "
"When using develop, maturin will copy the native library and for cffi also "
"the glue code to your python folder. You should add those files to your "
"gitignore."
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:180
msgid ""
"With cffi you can do `from .my_project import lib` and then use `lib."
"my_native_function`, with pyo3/rust-cpython you can directly `from ."
"my_project import my_native_function`."
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:182
msgid "Example layout with pyo3 after `maturin develop`:"
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:196
msgid ""
"When doing this also be sure to set the module name in your code to match "
"the last part of `module-name` (don't include the package path):"
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:198
msgid ""
"```\n"
"#[pymodule]\n"
"#[pyo3(name=\"_lib_name\")]\n"
"fn my_lib_name(_py: Python<'_>, m: &PyModule) -> PyResult<()> {\n"
"    m.add_class::<MyPythonRustClass>()?;\n"
"    Ok(())\n"
"}\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:208
msgid "Python metadata"
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:210
msgid ""
"maturin supports [PEP 621](https://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0621/), you "
"can specify python package metadata in `pyproject.toml`. maturin merges "
"metadata from `Cargo.toml` and `pyproject.toml`, `pyproject.toml` take "
"precedence over `Cargo.toml`."
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:213
msgid ""
"To specify python dependencies, add a list `dependencies` in a `[project]` "
"section in the `pyproject.toml`. This list is equivalent to "
"`install_requires` in setuptools:"
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:215
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"[project]\n"
"name = \"my-project\"\n"
"dependencies = [\"flask~=1.1.0\", \"toml==0.10.0\"]\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:221
msgid ""
"Pip allows adding so called console scripts, which are shell commands that "
"execute some function in you program. You can add console scripts in a "
"section `[project.scripts]`. The keys are the script names while the values "
"are the path to the function in the format `some.module.path:class."
"function`, where the `class` part is optional. The function is called with "
"no arguments. Example:"
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:224
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"[project.scripts]\n"
"get_42 = \"my_project:DummyClass.get_42\"\n"
"```"
msgstr ""
"```toml\n"
"[project.scripts]\n"
"get_42 = \"my_project:DummyClass.get_42\"\n"
"```"

#: src/index.md:229
msgid ""
"You can also specify [trove classifiers](https://pypi.org/classifiers/) in "
"your `pyproject.toml` under `project.classifiers`:"
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:231
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"[project]\n"
"name = \"my-project\"\n"
"classifiers = [\"Programming Language :: Python\"]\n"
"```"
msgstr ""
"```toml\n"
"[project]\n"
"name = \"my-project\"\n"
"classifiers = [\"Programming Language :: Python\"]\n"
"```"

#: src/index.md:237
msgid "Source distribution"
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:239
msgid ""
"maturin supports building through `pyproject.toml`. To use it, create a "
"`pyproject.toml` next to your `Cargo.toml` with the following content:"
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:241
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"[build-system]\n"
"requires = [\"maturin>=0.14,<0.15\"]\n"
"build-backend = \"maturin\"\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:247
msgid ""
"If a `pyproject.toml` with a `[build-system]` entry is present, maturin can "
"build a source distribution of your package when `--sdist` is specified. The "
"source distribution will contain the same files as `cargo package`. To only "
"build a source distribution, pass `--interpreter` without any values."
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:250
msgid ""
"You can then e.g. install your package with `pip install .`. With `pip "
"install . -v` you can see the output of cargo and maturin."
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:252
msgid ""
"You can use the options `compatibility`, `skip-auditwheel`, `bindings`, "
"`strip` and common Cargo build options such as `features` under `[tool."
"maturin]` the same way you would when running maturin directly. The "
"`bindings` key is required for cffi and bin projects as those can't be "
"automatically detected. Currently, all builds are in release mode (see [this "
"thread](https://discuss.python.org/t/pep-517-debug-vs-release-builds/1924) "
"for details)."
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:255
msgid ""
"For a non-manylinux build with cffi bindings you could use the following:"
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:257
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"[build-system]\n"
"requires = [\"maturin>=0.14,<0.15\"]\n"
"build-backend = \"maturin\"\n"
"\n"
"[tool.maturin]\n"
"bindings = \"cffi\"\n"
"compatibility = \"linux\"\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:267
msgid ""
"`manylinux` option is also accepted as an alias of `compatibility` for "
"backward compatibility with old version of maturin."
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:269
msgid ""
"To include arbitrary files in the sdist for use during compilation specify "
"`include` as an array of `path` globs with `format` set to `sdist`:"
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:271
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"[tool.maturin]\n"
"include = [{ path = \"path/**/*\", format = \"sdist\" }]\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:276
msgid ""
"There's a `maturin sdist` command for only building a source distribution as "
"workaround for [pypa/pip#6041](https://github.com/pypa/pip/issues/6041)."
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:278
msgid "Manylinux and auditwheel"
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:280
msgid ""
"For portability reasons, native python modules on linux must only "
"dynamically link a set of very few libraries which are installed basically "
"everywhere, hence the name manylinux. The pypa offers special docker images "
"and a tool called [auditwheel](https://github.com/pypa/auditwheel/) to "
"ensure compliance with the [manylinux rules](https://peps.python.org/"
"pep-0599/#the-manylinux2014-policy). If you want to publish widely usable "
"wheels for linux pypi, **you need to use a manylinux docker image**."
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:284
msgid ""
"The Rust compiler since version 1.64 [requires at least glibc 2.17](https://"
"blog.rust-lang.org/2022/08/01/Increasing-glibc-kernel-requirements.html), so "
"you need to use at least manylinux2014. For publishing, we recommend "
"enforcing the same manylinux version as the image with the manylinux flag, e."
"g. use `--manylinux 2014` if you are building in `quay.io/pypa/"
"manylinux2014_x86_64`. The [PyO3/maturin-action](https://github.com/PyO3/"
"maturin-action) github action already takes care of this if you set e.g. "
"`manylinux: 2014`."
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:288
msgid ""
"maturin contains a reimplementation of auditwheel automatically checks the "
"generated library and gives the wheel the proper. If your system's glibc is "
"too new or you link other shared libraries, it will assign the `linux` tag. "
"You can also manually disable those checks and directly use native linux "
"target with `--manylinux off`."
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:292
msgid ""
"For full manylinux compliance you need to compile in a CentOS docker "
"container. The [pyo3/maturin](https://ghcr.io/pyo3/maturin) image is based "
"on the manylinux2014 image, and passes arguments to the `maturin` binary. "
"You can use it like this:"
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:299
msgid ""
"Note that this image is very basic and only contains python, maturin and "
"stable rust. If you need additional tools, you can run commands inside the "
"manylinux container. See [konstin/complex-manylinux-maturin-docker](https://"
"github.com/konstin/complex-manylinux-maturin-docker) for a small educational "
"example or [nanoporetech/fast-ctc-decode](https://github.com/nanoporetech/"
"fast-ctc-decode/blob/b226ea0f2b2f4f474eff47349703d57d2ea4801b/.github/"
"workflows/publish.yml) for a real world setup."
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:302
msgid ""
"maturin itself is manylinux compliant when compiled for the musl target."
msgstr ""

